<Review ID>4657403
<Product Name>Philips HDD1630 6 GB MP3 Player
<Title>Perfection marred by crappy software
<Date>Tue Jan 17 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>The Philips HDD1630 6gb is a lovely Mp3 player.  Sleek design, small size, lightweight, great sound. Unfortunately, the fact that this player is tied down to Windows Media Player AND ONLY Windows XP SP2, makes on NOT want to purchase this unit.    The player itself is nice.  The screen is bright, colorful and SKINNABLE.  So hopefully in the future we'll be able to download more skins for the UI of the players screen.  It pumps out good volume and the different equalizer settings will keep you jamming that much longer.  I personally didn't use any of the EQ settings and it still sounded great.  Navigating through the menus is quick and painfree, thanks to the simplified interface.  There are only two small complaints and that's the 1 or 2 pause between songs when you skip tracks, makes it almost feel like a CD player.  Second is the photo loading takes a bit longer than you might expect, but over all its an enjoyable experince.  UNTIL you get to the software! I know Windows Media Player LOOKS like a good way to use your music, but its not.  At first I thought it was just me and I was just a jaded person since i used an iPod before.  But i gave it to my sister, who has NEVER used an mp3 player, for a couple of days to use.  From her non-computer saavy perspective she said it was terrible to use.  I don't even want to get into all the craziness that I had with the software!  And I've been in the computing world for 17 years.  This would be an iPod killer.. but the software just ruins your experince.  Pros:  Great battery life small screen, nice screen, great features ON the player itself, the menu on the player is easy to navigate and the buttons look cool, skinnable UI on the player.  Cons: skipping songs on the player has a cd-player feel where it takes 1 - 2 seconds to load the next song.  Software is HORRIBLE!! The USB transfer cable / power cord could definitely use some redesigning.  
<Overall>3

<Review ID>3288407
<Product Name>Philips HDD1630 6 GB MP3 Player
<Title>BEST LOOKING PLAYER, but buggy design
<Date>Thu Jan 19 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>I've have done quite a bit of research and now have pretty good experience with several of the latest MP3 players. This is by far the best looking MP3 player in our ipod dominated world. I have used SanDisk Sansa M240 1gb, IRiver 1gb U10, the Creative Labs Micro Photo 8gb and this player.  PRO: 1) Looks. Sleek and shiny with a good screen. Nice blue lighted effects with the slider. 2) Good battery life. 3) Price. 4) Fairly decent headphones included. 5) SRS WOW - 3D sound, great on surround systems. 6) Touch Slider - All that I've tried seemed to be pretty tricky to get used to.  This is probally the best one I've used that comes close to the ipod.    CON: 1) Sound quality a little meager compared to what I've heard with other MP3 players better than the SanDisk but volume even on max setting is pretty low. 2) Buttons. I do agree its hard to make something look nice and be pretty functional. Because of being so sleek, with no tactile feedback, its can be hard navigate the player while doing other things such as driving or working out. I found this more as a little annoyance. 3) My biggest concern was the buggy interface on player itself. I believe it has problems with DRM windows media files, these are the files you download from the "All you can eat buffet" from subscription services. (Yahoo, Napster, & Real Rhapsody) This player would lockup or pause for an eternity several times and be unresponsive even to turn it off. I exchanged it for another one which came with exact same problems. My experience lockups occur more frequently while using playlists.  RECAP: To me this was a love hate relationship.  I loved how it looked and could see the potential of this player. But until they fix these bugs I would have a very hard time to recommend this product.  I almost kept it in hopes that Phillips may make a better firmware upgrade. I eventually went with the Creative Labs Micro Photo that has performed awesome. It just does not have the shiny finish and it is couple clicks lower on the "I'm Cool!" scale. Before you decide to buy, try searching for "HDD1630 freeze" and you will see variety of comments of this model and it's larger cousin that shares the same firmware HDD6330. I believe comments left here and many other reviews have not used the product at all or fully, I had used it for 2 weeks.   
<Overall>3

<Review ID>8223645
<Product Name>Philips HDD1630 6 GB MP3 Player
<Title>Style over substance, flash over function, etc.
<Date>Fri Jan 20 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>I recommend a healthy dose of skepticism with regards to this player's high average review score on Amazon.  The Philips' HDD1630 is high on looks and low in price (compared to similarly equipped players), but is unstable, behaves erratically, is often slow to respond or unresponsive altogether, illogically designed, and the sound quality isn't that good either (especially the bass).  After a month and a half of use, my own player started randomly adding the current song to the default playlist when I pressed *any* button, and even a system restore via the included software could not fix this problem.  It's certainly possible that some people own HDD1630s that are not buggy at all, but the apparently high probability of getting a buggy one (given the dissenting reviews) makes purchasing this player something of a crapshoot, so beware.  Instability: The player I owned periodically froze up, perhaps a couple times a week.  (This is a fairly negligible problem on its own, but within the player's larger constellation of flaws, is just another reason to stay away.)  Erratic behavior: More often than the player froze up, I would encounter strange problems with loading and playing songs.  For instance, the player might list a song twice, when I had only loaded it once.  It would often skip over certain songs, despite listing them, and would refuse to play them until I had reloaded them.  I think this is a problem with how the player constructs its database of songs.  Fwiw, I relied mainly on dragging files to the device through Windows Explorer, rather than using Media Player, though I believe the same problems occurred when I used Media Player.  Interface is slow to respond, unresponsive: The touch-sensitive "buttons" are very frequently unresponsive.  While the buttons themselves would consistently light up in response to a swipe of my thumb, the player itself would often not register any command.  Additionally, navigating through menus is awkwardly slow when music is playing.  You might hit a button and not receive any feedback until over a second has passed, and the menus themselves scroll slowly.  A second's delay doesn't sound like much, but in the world of electronic interfaces, such a delay constantly forces us to worry whether we need to repeat a command.  Well designed interfaces offer prompt, nigh-instantaneous feedback.  Perhaps if Philips had cut down on the graphical content, the player might've been able to do so.  Mediocre sound quality: Having recently purchased an iPod shuffle, I found it remarkable how much better the sound quality was in comparison to the Philips HDD1630 (using the same pair of headphones).  The shuffle's sound is much richer and offers high quality bass, whereas the HDD1630 sounds mechanically produced in comparison, and the bass level cannot be much increased from its default setting without generating noticeable distortion.  On the plus side, the player does not scratch easily: I carried it unprotected in my pocket (making sure not to put any abrasive objects next to it) for as long as I owned it, and it failed to scratch at all.  All things considered, though, I'd rather have a scratched yet stable player than a cosmetically flawless and buggy one.  Don't be fooled by its good looks or tempted by its low price.  I *strongly* advise looking (or waiting) for a different player.  
<Overall>2

<Review ID>0001959
<Product Name>Philips HDD1630 6 GB MP3 Player
<Title>Absolutely LOVE this player
<Date>Sun Jan 22 00:00:00 CST 2006
<Content>I have no idea why some other reviewers don't like this player.  I've had no problems at all.... so here's my complete review.  I've done a lot of research while searching for my next Digital Audio Player.  I had a Creative Muvo 256 mb player (my first DAP) which I was looking to upgrade because I wanted A LOT more space.  When searching for a new one I knew I wanted these features:  Color screen, at least 5 GB of space, FM, jpeg display, album art display, and voice recording capabilities.  Looks were at the bottom of my list, but I admit, this is a great looking player.    I knew the ipods were going to be WAY out of my price range and they don't have all the features I wanted anyway.  Originally, I ran into what I thought was a deal on a $95 5GB DAP, the japanese NHJ VHD-5100.  That was the crappiest player to ever exist.  It locked up on me literally hours after taking it out of the box so I returned it.  (Do NOT buy that one if you happen to find it somewhere).  You get what you pay for, so my search began for better one.  I decided on the Philips GoGear HDD1630 because it had all the features I wanted so I decided to fork out the extra $80 bucks after returning the VHD-5100.  MONEY WELL SPENT.  WHAT I LIKE: - Plenty of space for my music (currently have about 800 songs with lots of room to spare) - Looks sleek, I like the black color, has the neat blue touch-sensitive lighted controls - The sound is MUCH better than my Creative Muvo - I LOVE the headphones supplied with the player.  I have smaller ears and they fit perfectly and sound great - Album art displays with each song (kind of small but there nonetheless) - FM radio, w/ FM recording feature - Voice recording (I like to record my husband snoring and let him hear how ANNOYING he is - LOL) - Slide show jpeg display... I like to show off my kids every once in a while :-) - Great battery life - The price (you get A LOT for your money)  WHAT I DON'T LIKE (very little): - The front of the player smudges a lot (not a big deal to me) - The sound settings are a little strange, some of them sound muffled.  I've had the best luck with the SRS WOW setting. - No case w/ belt clip supplied with the player.  But you can buy a leather Philips one at Wal-Mart for $9.88.  LOADING SONGS ONTO THE PLAYER: VERY EASY.  Despite what others have said, the player was CAKE to load with my 800 songs.  Windows Media Player is NOT that hard to use.  A monkey could do it.  I have no idea what kind of person could not figure this out.  And even if you don't like WMP, you can also drag & drop through Windows Explorer.    ALBUM ART TIP: Some of my album art did not display initially.  A quick visit to the FAQ on the Philips site solved the issue.  All you need to do is place the album art jpeg file in the album folder using windows explorer, and name it "Album Art.jpg".  That simple.  It works best if you make sure your jpeg file is less than 4k, that way it displays on the player quicker.   BOTTOM LINE: This player far exceeded my expectations.  It was simple to use and very easy to load songs on.  If you're not an idiot and do it correctly in the first place, IT IS VERY USER-FRIENDLY.  I would definitely recommend this player to anyone.  
<Overall>5

